<doc id="237868" wikidata="Q919107" url="?curid=237868" title="Product (category theory)">
<text>In category theory, the product of two (or more) objects in a category is a notion designed to capture the essence behind constructions in other areas of mathematics such as the Cartesian product of sets, the direct product of groups or rings, and the product of topological spaces. Essentially, the product of a family of objects is the &quot;most general&quot; object which admits a morphism to each of the given objects.

==Definition==

===Product of two objects===

Fix a category formula_1 Let formula_2 and formula_3 be objects of formula_1 A product of formula_2 and formula_3 is an object formula_7 typically denoted formula_8 equipped with a pair of morphisms formula_9 formula_10 satisfying the following universal property:
* For every object formula_11 and every pair of morphisms formula_12 formula_13 there exists a unique morphism formula_14 such that the following diagram commutes:

Whether a product exists may depend on formula_15 or on formula_2 and formula_17 If it does exist, it is unique up to canonical isomorphism, because of the universal property, so one may speak of &quot;the&quot; product. This has the following meaning: if formula_18 is another product, there exists a unique isomorphism formula_19 such that formula_20 and formula_21.

The morphisms formula_22 and formula_23 are called the canonical projections or projection morphisms; the letter formula_24 alliterates with projection. Given formula_11 and formula_26 formula_27 the unique morphism formula_28 is called the product of morphisms formula_29 and formula_30 and is denoted formula_31

===Product of an arbitrary family===

Instead of two objects, we can start with an arbitrary family of objects indexed by a set formula_32

Given a family formula_33 of objects, a product of the family is an object formula_34 equipped with morphisms formula_35 satisfying the following universal property: 
*For every object formula_11 and every formula_37-indexed family of morphisms formula_38 there exists a unique morphism formula_39 such that the following diagrams commute for all formula_40

The product is denoted formula_41 If formula_42 then it is denoted formula_43 and the product of morphisms is denoted formula_44

===Equational definition===

Alternatively, the product may be defined through equations. So, for example, for the binary product:
* Existence of formula_28 is guaranteed by existence of the operation formula_46
* Commutativity of the diagrams above is guaranteed by the equality: for all formula_47 and all formula_48 formula_49
* Uniqueness of formula_28 is guaranteed by the equality: for all formula_51 formula_52

===As a limit===

The product is a special case of a limit. This may be seen by using a discrete category (a family of objects without any morphisms, other than their identity morphisms) as the diagram required for the definition of the limit. The discrete objects will serve as the index of the components and projections. If we regard this diagram as a functor, it is a functor from the index set formula_37 considered as a discrete category. The definition of the product then coincides with the definition of the limit, formula_54 being a cone and projections being the limit (limiting cone).

===Universal property===

Just as the limit is a special case of the universal construction, so is the product. Starting with the definition given for the universal property of limits, take formula_55 as the discrete category with two objects, so that formula_56 is simply the product category formula_57 The diagonal functor formula_58 assigns to each object formula_34 the ordered pair formula_60 and to each morphism formula_28 the pair formula_62 The product formula_63 in formula_15 is given by a universal morphism from the functor formula_65 to the object formula_66 in formula_57 This universal morphism consists of an object formula_34 of formula_15 and a morphism formula_70 which contains projections.

==Examples==
In the category of sets, the product (in the category theoretic sense) is the Cartesian product. Given a family of sets formula_71 the product is defined as
formula_72
with the canonical projections
formula_73

Given any set formula_11 with a family of functions formula_38 
the universal arrow formula_76 is defined by formula_77

Other examples:
* In the category of topological spaces, the product is the space whose underlying set is the Cartesian product and which carries the product topology. The product topology is the coarsest topology for which all the projections are continuous.
* In the category of modules over some ring formula_78 the product is the Cartesian product with addition defined componentwise and distributive multiplication.
* In the category of groups, the product is the direct product of groups given by the Cartesian product with multiplication defined componentwise.
* In the category of graphs, the product is the tensor product of graphs.
* In the category of relations, the product is given by the disjoint union. (This may come as a bit of a surprise given that the category of sets is a subcategory of the category of relations.)
* In the category of algebraic varieties, the product is given by the Segre embedding.
* In the category of semi-abelian monoids, the product is given by the history monoid.
* In the category of Banach spaces and short maps, the product carries the  norm. 
* A partially ordered set can be treated as a category, using the order relation as the morphisms. In this case the products and coproducts correspond to greatest lower bounds (meets) and least upper bounds (joins).

==Discussion==

An example in which the product does not exist: In the category of fields, the product formula_79 does not exist, since there is no field with homomorphisms to both formula_80 and formula_81

Another example: An empty product (that is, formula_37 is the empty set) is the same as a terminal object, and some categories, such as the category of infinite groups, do not have a terminal object: given any infinite group formula_83 there are infinitely many morphisms formula_84 so formula_83 cannot be terminal.

If formula_37 is a set such that all products for families indexed with formula_37 exist, then one can treat each product as a functor formula_88 How this functor maps objects is obvious. Mapping of morphisms is subtle, because the product of morphisms defined above does not fit. First, consider the binary product functor, which is a bifunctor. For formula_89 we should find a morphism formula_90 We choose formula_91 This operation on morphisms is called Cartesian product of morphisms. Second, consider the general product functor. For families formula_92 we should find a morphism formula_93 We choose the product of morphisms formula_94

A category where every finite set of objects has a product is sometimes called a Cartesian category
(although some authors use this phrase to mean &quot;a category with all finite limits&quot;).

The product is associative. Suppose formula_15 is a Cartesian category, product functors have been chosen as above, and formula_96 denotes a terminal object of formula_1 We then have natural isomorphisms
formula_98
formula_99
formula_100
These properties are formally similar to those of a commutative monoid; a Cartesian category with its finite products is an example of a symmetric monoidal category.

==Distributivity==

For any objects formula_101 of a category with finite products and coproducts, there is a canonical morphism formula_102 where the plus sign here denotes the coproduct. To see this, note that the universal property of the coproduct formula_103 guarantees the existence of unique arrows filling out the following diagram (the induced arrows are dashed):

The universal property of the product formula_104 then guarantees a unique morphism formula_105 induced by the dashed arrows in the above diagram. A distributive category is one in which this morphism is actually an isomorphism. Thus in a distributive category, there is the canonical isomorphism
formula_106

